# Authoring Git Commit Rules (`.mdc`)

Meta-guide for agents and maintainers who **create or update** a project-specific Git commit rule (for example `git-commits.mdc`). This file is **not** the commit policy itself — it teaches how to write one.

Follow [cursor-rules.mdc](cursor-rules.mdc) for file placement and frontmatter. Do not duplicate the full [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/en/v1.0.0/) specification inside generated rules.

---

## Where the rule file belongs

| Requirement | Detail |
|-------------|--------|
| Location | `PROJECT_ROOT/.cursor/rules/` only |
| Filename | kebab-case, `.mdc` extension, purpose-clear (e.g. `git-commits.mdc`, `git-commit-policy.mdc`) |
| Forbidden | Project root, `docs/`, package folders, or any path outside `.cursor/rules/` |

Suggested layout:

```txt
.cursor/rules/
├── cursor-rules.mdc
├── git-commit-rules.mdc    # this meta-guide
└── git-commits.mdc         # project policy (you author per repo)
```

---

## Neutral frontmatter

Keep frontmatter **portable** and **discovery-friendly**:

```yaml
---
description: Conventional commit format, scope inference, and commit/push authorization for this repository
globs:
alwaysApply: false
---
```

| Field | Guidance |
|-------|----------|
| `description` | Third person; state **what** the rule does and **when** to use it (commit, push, branch naming, message drafting). No product or framework names unless the repo itself is named in user docs. |
| `globs` | Optional. Omit or leave empty unless the rule should attach when editing certain paths (e.g. only when touching `.cursor/rules/`). Most commit rules use no globs. |
| `alwaysApply` | Prefer `false`. Commit rules are invoked when the user asks for commits or when the agent drafts messages — not on every turn. |

Avoid `alwaysApply: true` unless the repository explicitly wants commit policy on every request.

---

## Keep the generated rule reusable

A good project commit rule is **short, operational, and local**:

1. **Separate meta from policy** — This file explains authoring; the generated `git-commits.mdc` (or similar) holds the repo policy.
2. **Link upward, not outward** — Use relative links to other rules in the same folder (see [Links](#links)).
3. **No frozen inventory** — Do not paste a fixed list of scopes, packages, or apps from one repo into a template meant for all repos.
4. **Teach inference** — Tell the agent how to **derive** scopes from the current tree (see [Scope inference](#scope-inference)).
5. **Placeholder examples only** — Use `type`, `scope`, `short summary` in examples, not real module names from a past project.
6. **Point to external spec once** — One link to Conventional Commits; summarize types in a small table instead of copying RFC-style MUST/SHALL blocks.

---

## Commit authorization boundaries

Every generated commit rule **must** state when git write operations are allowed. Adapt wording to the repo; keep boundaries explicit.

### Default boundaries (recommended)

| Action | Rule |
|--------|------|
| `git commit` | Only when the user **explicitly** requests a commit in the current turn (or a user rule overrides). |
| `git push` | Only when the user **explicitly** requests push. Do not offer push proactively. |
| `git commit --amend` | Only when user rules allow amend (e.g. hook fixed files, unpushed HEAD, user said amend). |
| Destructive git | No `push --force`, `reset --hard`, or similar unless the user explicitly requests and understands impact. |
| `git config` | Do not change local or global git config for the user. |

### Clarification behavior

- If the user says “save this” or “finish up” without saying **commit**, ask whether they want a commit or only file changes.
- Before committing, **inspect** what will be included; exclude unrelated paths unless the user approves a broader commit.
- When authorization is unclear, **confirm** before any write operation.

Include a short **“Before committing”** checklist in the generated rule (status, diff, scope of changes, secrets check).

---

## Conventional Commits (compact, not a spec dump)

In the generated rule, include only:

### Format

```txt
<type>[optional scope][optional !]: <description>

[optional body]

[optional footer]
```

### Types table (typical)

| Type | Intent |
|------|--------|
| `feat` | New behavior or capability |
| `fix` | Bug fix |
| `docs` | Documentation only |
| `test` | Tests only |
| `refactor` | Code change without intended behavior change |
| `chore` | Maintenance, tooling, deps |
| `build` | Build system or generated artifacts |
| `ci` | CI configuration |
| `perf` | Performance improvement |
| `style` | Formatting-only |

Add other types only if the repository already uses them consistently.

### Subject line habits

- Imperative mood (`add`, `fix`, `remove`, not `added`)
- Lowercase summary (no trailing period unless team style says otherwise)
- Short (aim for ≤ 72 characters)
- Describe **intent**, not file names only

### Breaking changes

One paragraph: use `!` after type/scope or a `BREAKING CHANGE:` footer when public API, config shape, or consumer contracts change. Link to [Conventional Commits — breaking change](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/en/v1.0.0/#commit-message-with-description-and-breaking-change-footer) instead of reproducing the full rules.

**Do not** paste the entire Conventional Commits specification or Angular commitlint appendix into `.mdc` files.

---

## Scope inference (repository-specific, not hardcoded)

Instruct the agent to **discover** scopes when authoring or applying the project commit rule:

1. Read the repository layout: monorepo manifests (`pnpm-workspace.yaml`, `lerna.json`, `nx.json`, `turbo.json`), top-level `apps/`, `packages/`, `services/`, `crates/`, etc.
2. Prefer **one primary scope per commit** matching the owning area of most changes.
3. Derive scope names from **folder names** or **published package names** (last segment of package name), normalized to lowercase kebab-case.
4. Use cross-cutting scopes only when appropriate (`docs`, `ci`, `deps`, `repo`) — define them in the generated rule **after** inspecting the repo, not from a global template list.
5. For documentation-only or root-tooling changes, use `docs` or `repo` (or omit scope if the team allows).
6. If a change spans multiple owners, **split commits** or document all areas in the body — do not invent a vague scope.

Template paragraph for generated rules:

> **Scopes:** Infer from this repository’s directory and package layout. Do not use scopes from other projects. When unsure, inspect `git diff --stat` and match the path prefix that owns the majority of lines changed.

---

## Avoid project-specific examples in templates

When writing or updating a **reusable** commit rule template:

| Do | Don't |
|----|--------|
| `feat(scope): add validation for install paths` | Names of internal packages, apps, or frameworks |
| `fix(scope): prevent duplicate config merge` | Real ticket IDs unless user supplies them |
| `docs: clarify configuration format` | “Always run X script” tied to one repo’s scripts |
| Placeholder `scope` in every example | Copy-paste examples from another repository’s git log |

After cloning a template into a repo, **one** maintenance pass may add a small “Scopes in this repository” table — that table belongs in the **project** `git-commits.mdc`, not in this neutral meta-guide.

---

## Safe git workflow commands

Include non-interactive commands suitable for agents. Prefer modern Git when available:

```bash
git status --short
git diff
git diff --staged
git log -5 --oneline
git add -- <path>
git restore --staged -- <path>
git restore -- <path>
git switch -c <branch>
git switch <branch>
```

Commit (only after authorization):

```bash
git commit -m "$(cat <<'EOF'
type(scope): short summary

Optional body paragraph.

EOF
)"
```

HEREDOC-style messages reduce shell-escaping mistakes on Unix shells. On Windows shells, use the platform-appropriate equivalent the user environment supports.

### Practices to document in generated rules

- Run `git status` and `git diff` before staging.
- Stage **paths**, not `git add -A`, unless the user wants everything.
- Never use `-i` / interactive commands (no `git add -i`, `rebase -i`).
- Do not skip hooks (`--no-verify`) unless the user explicitly requests it.
- Do not push unless explicitly requested.

Optional trailers (Co-authored-by, Signed-off-by): only if the repository or user rules require them — do not invent trailers in the neutral template.

