## Links

Use **relative** Markdown links only — files in the same repo, same rule folder when possible:

| Link target | Example |
|-------------|---------|
| Rule authoring | [cursor-rules.mdc](cursor-rules.mdc) |
| This meta-guide | [git-commit-rules.mdc](git-commit-rules.mdc) |
| Project commit policy | [git-commits.mdc](git-commits.mdc) *(if present)* |

Do not use `mdc:` URLs or absolute paths to another developer’s machine.

External specs: full URL once (Conventional Commits, optional Conventional Branch), not duplicated in prose.

---

## Checklist: creating `git-commits.mdc` for a repository

1. Create `.cursor/rules/git-commits.mdc` per [cursor-rules.mdc](cursor-rules.mdc).
2. Write neutral `description` and `alwaysApply: false`.
3. Add **authorization** section (commit / push / amend / destructive).
4. Add compact **Conventional Commits** section (format + types table + breaking note).
5. Add **scope inference** instructions tied to **this repo’s** layout (discovered at apply time, not copied from elsewhere).
6. Add **before commit** steps (`status`, `diff`, secrets, unrelated files).
7. Add **safe commands** block (non-interactive).
8. Add 3–5 **placeholder** examples (`type(scope): …`).
9. Link to [cursor-rules.mdc](cursor-rules.mdc) and, if useful, [git-commit-rules.mdc](git-commit-rules.mdc).
10. Keep the file under ~150 lines unless the repository has exceptional needs.

---

## Good vs bad meta-authoring

```markdown
<!-- Good: teaches inference -->
Scopes are derived from top-level folders under `packages/` and `apps/`.

<!-- Bad: hardcodes another project -->
Use scopes: tokens, ui, registry, cli.
```

```markdown
<!-- Good: boundary -->
Run `git commit` only when the user explicitly asks for a commit.

<!-- Bad: vague -->
Be careful with git.
```

```markdown
<!-- Good: link -->
See [cursor-rules.mdc](cursor-rules.mdc).

<!-- Bad: absolute -->
See file:///C:/Users/dev/project/.cursor/rules/cursor-rules.mdc
```
